Compared to `convert`, the `as` method:
1. provides type assertion which is useful if you consider the number of times expressions like `convert(T,x)::T` appear in Julia base code and many other Julia packages;
2. has the ability to build a callable object for conversion, like `isequal` and a few other functions;
3. can be extended to behave differently than `convert` for some specific types while perserving the semantic that it yields an object of the requested type and avoiding type-piracy. For instance the `CartesianIndex` constructor may be called to convert a tuple of integers to a Cartesian index but `convert(CartesiaIndex,x)` cannot do that.

Otherwise, using `as` is mostly a matter of improving code readability for a common type of operation. I may be a bit paranoid on type-stability but making sure that parameters have a given stable type is something I do a lot, in particular for real-time applications.
